UNDIAGNOSED TOXIN - ALGERIA: (SKIKDA) CANDY SUSPECTED, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
******************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 6 Jun 2022
Source: Al-Chorouk Online [in Arabic, machine trans., edited]
https://bit.ly/3aQqrGD


Since the dawn of Sunday [5 Jun 2022], the medical emergency department at Abdelkader Natour Hospital in the city of Skikda has received 18 people, ranging in age from 23 to 57 years, who showed symptoms of severe poisoning represented by high body temperature and vomiting accompanied by diarrhea and nausea.

According to what hospital sources revealed to Al-Chorouk, the cases received by the emergency department were sporadic and at different times, as 4 affected women were transferred from the Al-Sharaa municipality at dawn on Sunday [5 Jun 2022] to the emergency department after suffering from continuous vomiting and diarrhea, where they were given the necessary treatment.

Before leaving the hospital, while the number of people affected with food poisoning increased in the evening of the same day, reaching 14 patients, including children, all suffering from the same symptoms, 4 of them were placed under medical supervision due to the seriousness of their health condition, while the others were allowed to leave after receiving the necessary treatment.

Our sources added during the interrogation of the affected by the doctors, they all confirmed they ate sweets (candies) and refreshments on the same day in one of the shops in the city of Al-Qul.

At the same time, the concerned authorities represented by the services of the Directorate of Trade and the services of Hygiene, together with the services of the Directorate of Health and Security, began their investigations to find out the causes of this mass poisoning. The incident came with the beginning of the summer season.

On the other hand, our sources stated over Sunday night and Monday morning [5-6 Jun 2022] several (cases) that arrived at the hospital were registered after suffering from the same symptoms, bringing the total number to about 30 cases.

[Byline: Zubaida Bodmagagh]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

[Vomiting and diarrhea are relatively non-specific signs associated with many gastrointestinal (GI) distress.

If there is more evidence or a firm diagnosis from knowledgeable sources, ProMED would appreciate the information. - Mod.TG

